URL: &lt;a href=&quot;https://git.openjdk.org/jdk/pull/15409&quot;&gt;https://git.openjdk.org/jdk/pull/15409&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br/&gt;
Date: 2023-08-24 00:53:03 +0000</comment>
                            <comment id="14606194" author="andrew" created="Wed, 23 Aug 2023 11:40:13 -0700"  >Reopening this as it&amp;#39;s still an issue.&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;br/&gt;
Users should be able to use an installed pcsclite.so.1 without having to install the development package for the library or pass command-line options every time. For compatibility, we can keep the previous unversioned check but prefer those that are known to work (pcsclite.so.1 and apparently pcsclite.so.0, though Solaris is no longer supported by modern JDKs) as pcsclite.so could potentially link to a pcsclite.so.2 which the JDK is incompatible with.&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;br/&gt;
We&amp;#39;ve had a better patch for this for a long time and I&amp;#39;ll open a PR with it shortly.&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;br/&gt;
</comment>
                            <comment id="14233675" author="mullan" created="Thu, 3 Jan 2019 12:44:05 -0800"  >The submitter has fixed this upstream in their own JDK implementation and there is already a workaround using a system property, so I don&amp;#39;t think there is any need to keep this bug open anymore.</comment>
                            <comment id="13313220" author="valeriep" created="Thu, 11 Apr 2013 17:34:23 -0700"  >Quite a few Solaris systems only have libpcsclite.so.0. So, cannot simply change to loading libpcsclite.so.1.&lt;br/&gt;
Need to keep backward compatibility.</comment>
